    <div class="content">

        <!-- SECTION 1: THE SITUATION -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>📍 The Situation: CEO Managing ADHD and Business Growth</h2>

            <div class="key-quote">
                "Block scheduling is really good for ADHD people because it puts you in blocks and you don't have to do the same thing every day, but you have to do something in that area every day."
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>Your Context</h4>
                <p><strong>Your role:</strong> CEO of a small business, managing operations, vendors, and staff</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Current medications:</strong> Vyvanse and Adderall for ADHD</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>What you're navigating:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Multiple responsibilities and roles in your business</li>
                    <li>Challenges with time management and organization</li>
                    <li>Business growth and strategic planning needs</li>
                    <li>Clarifying company mission and values</li>
                    <li>Concerns about medication effects and dependency</li>
                    <li>Balancing productivity with well-being</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>What You're Seeking</h4>
                <p><strong>Your goals:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Greater productivity and organization (personal and professional)</li>
                    <li>Optimal medication use without dependency</li>
                    <li>Consistent motivation and energy throughout the day</li>
                    <li>Structured approach to managing multiple roles</li>
                    <li>Clear business values and mission</li>
                    <li>Reduced feelings of overwhelm</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SECTION 2: CORE PROBLEM -->
        <div class="section page-break">
            <h2>🎯 The Core Problem: Inconsistency, Overwhelm & Unclear Direction</h2>

            <div class="key-quote">
                "Your mission and values and purpose — those should come from feelings."
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>The Challenge: Maintaining Consistency</h4>
                <p><strong>What's happening:</strong> Struggle to maintain consistent motivation, energy, and organization throughout the day</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> You're juggling multiple roles, and inconsistency leads to:</p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Feeling scattered and reactive</li>
                    <li>Important areas getting neglected</li>
                    <li>Difficulty prioritizing</li>
                    <li>Energy crashes at crucial times</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>The Risk: Psychological Dependency on Medication</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> Feeling like you "need" medication to function, even if not physically addicted</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>The pattern to avoid:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Taking medication outside prescribed needs</li>
                    <li>Believing you can't be productive without it</li>
                    <li>Developing tolerance requiring higher doses</li>
                    <li>Brain reducing its own neurotransmitter production</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>The Gap: Lack of Structure and Values</h4>
                <p><strong>Time management:</strong> Without structured time blocks, you're contributing to overwhelm and inefficiency</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Business direction:</strong> Your business lacks clearly articulated values and emotional goals</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Impact:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Branding feels unclear or generic</li>
                    <li>Stakeholder experience is inconsistent</li>
                    <li>Decision-making lacks clear framework</li>
                    <li>Mission doesn't resonate emotionally</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="insight-box">
                <strong>The solution approach:</strong> Optimize medication use, implement structured time management, and clarify emotional values.
                <br><br>
                <strong>The goal:</strong> Sustainable productivity without dependency, organized days without overwhelm, authentic business direction.
            </div>
        </div>


        <!-- FRAMEWORK 1: MEDICATION OPTIMIZATION -->
        <div class="section page-break">
            <h2>💊 Framework #1: Medication Optimization</h2>

            <div class="key-quote">
                "As long as you take them as prescribed, you'll be fine."
            </div>

            <h3>The Four-Step Process</h3>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">1</span> Understand the Difference: Vyvanse vs. Adderall</h4>
                
                <p><strong>Vyvanse (Long-Acting):</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li><strong>Effect:</strong> Subtle, sustained focus throughout the day</li>
                    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 10-14 hours</li>
                    <li><strong>Onset:</strong> Gradual, smooth start</li>
                    <li><strong>Best for:</strong> All-day coverage, steady motivation</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:20px;"><strong>Adderall (Short-Acting):</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li><strong>Effect:</strong> Stronger, immediate boost</li>
                    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 4-6 hours</li>
                    <li><strong>Onset:</strong> Quick, noticeable start</li>
                    <li><strong>Best for:</strong> When you need extra focus or energy</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Understanding each medication helps you use them strategically</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">2</span> Use Both Medications Together in the Morning</h4>
                <p><strong>The combination approach:</strong> Take Vyvanse AND Adderall together in the morning as prescribed</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why combine them:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Vyvanse provides baseline, steady coverage</li>
                    <li>Adderall adds initial boost to get started</li>
                    <li>Together they achieve sufficient stimulation and motivation</li>
                    <li>Covers both immediate and long-term needs</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Current dosage:</strong> Small dose of Vyvanse + 5mg Adderall</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">3</span> Consider Increasing Vyvanse, Reserve Adderall for PRN</h4>
                <p><strong>The optimization strategy:</strong> May increase Vyvanse to 20mg for better all-day coverage</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>How this changes usage:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Higher Vyvanse dose = better sustained focus all day</li>
                    <li>Adderall becomes "as needed" (PRN) for afternoon or specific tasks</li>
                    <li>Reduces daily stimulant load</li>
                    <li>Less risk of tolerance or dependency</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The therapist's guidance:</strong> "You can take the Adderall as needed if you need it, like, in the afternoon or something for, like, PRN or as needed."</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">4</span> Take Medication Regularly During Workweek, Breaks on Weekends</h4>
                <p><strong>The weekly rhythm:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li><strong>Monday-Friday:</strong> Take medications as prescribed</li>
                    <li><strong>Saturday-Sunday:</strong> Skip or reduce medication</li>
                    <li><strong>Purpose:</strong> Medication holidays prevent tolerance and keep brain "online"</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Why weekend breaks matter:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Prevents brain from reducing its own neurotransmitter production</li>
                    <li>Avoids needing higher doses over time</li>
                    <li>Reduces risk of psychological dependency</li>
                    <li>Gives your system a reset</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The science:</strong> "The brain is supposed to do the job, but your brain is like, 'Oh, well, something else is doing that. I can stop.' That's how people get used to a medication and then they need higher doses."</p>
                
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The strategy:</strong> "Most people take a day or two over the weekend to keep their brain online and to keep the medication sort of working."</p>
            </div>

            <div class="strength-box">
                <h4>✓ Why This Framework Works</h4>
                <p><strong>Balances effectiveness with safety:</strong> You get the focus you need without overuse</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Prevents tolerance:</strong> Brain continues producing its own neurotransmitters</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Reduces dependency risk:</strong> Both psychological and physiological</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Sustainable long-term:</strong> Won't need constantly increasing doses</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FRAMEWORK 2: BLOCK SCHEDULING -->
        <div class="section page-break">
            <h2>📅 Framework #2: Blocked Time Schedule</h2>

            <div class="key-quote">
                "The first thing that I think that you'll have to establish is a blocked time schedule."
            </div>

            <h3>The Four-Step Process</h3>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">1</span> Identify Broad "Areas of Life"</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> List the major categories that matter in your life</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Examples of areas:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li><strong>Personal Development</strong> — Learning, growth, self-care</li>
                    <li><strong>Work</strong> — Business operations, strategy, leadership</li>
                    <li><strong>Family</strong> — Relationships, quality time</li>
                    <li><strong>Fitness</strong> — Exercise, health, wellness</li>
                    <li><strong>Social</strong> — Friends, community, connection</li>
                    <li><strong>Creative</strong> — Hobbies, passion projects</li>
                    <li><strong>Rest</strong> — Sleep, downtime, recovery</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Ensures all important areas receive attention, not just urgent work demands</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">2</span> Allocate Daily Time Blocks to Each Area</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> Assign specific time blocks to each life area every day</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Example daily structure:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li><strong>6:00-7:00 AM:</strong> Personal Development (reading, meditation, planning)</li>
                    <li><strong>7:00-8:00 AM:</strong> Fitness (workout, movement)</li>
                    <li><strong>8:00-12:00 PM:</strong> Work - Deep Focus</li>
                    <li><strong>12:00-1:00 PM:</strong> Rest/Lunch</li>
                    <li><strong>1:00-5:00 PM:</strong> Work - Operations & Meetings</li>
                    <li><strong>5:00-6:00 PM:</strong> Work - Email & Admin</li>
                    <li><strong>6:00-9:00 PM:</strong> Family Time</li>
                    <li><strong>9:00-10:00 PM:</strong> Personal (wind down)</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The flexibility:</strong> Activities within blocks can vary, but each area gets daily attention</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why this works for ADHD:</strong> "Block scheduling is really good for ADHD people because it puts you in blocks and you don't have to do the same thing every day, but you have to do something in that area every day."</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">3</span> Within "Work," Create Sub-Blocks for Specific Tasks</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> Break down your work time into focused task blocks</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Example work sub-blocks:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li><strong>Business Development:</strong> Strategy, growth, partnerships</li>
                    <li><strong>Operations Management:</strong> Vendor coordination, staff oversight</li>
                    <li><strong>Email Management:</strong> Inbox processing (not reactive all day)</li>
                    <li><strong>Client Relations:</strong> Meetings, relationship building</li>
                    <li><strong>Financial Review:</strong> Budget, billing, forecasting</li>
                    <li><strong>Creative Work:</strong> Marketing, branding, content</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The benefit:</strong> Instead of reacting to every email or request as it comes, you have set times for specific work types</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Example:</strong> Email block at 5:00-6:00 PM means you process all emails then, freeing mental space during deep work blocks</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">4</span> Use the Schedule to Streamline Thinking and Reduce Overwhelm</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> The schedule removes constant decision-making about what to do next</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>How it streamlines thinking:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>You know what category of work to focus on each block</li>
                    <li>No more "what should I do now?" paralysis</li>
                    <li>Reduced mental load from constant prioritization</li>
                    <li>Clear boundaries between work types</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>How it maintains balance:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Personal development doesn't get sacrificed for work</li>
                    <li>Family time is protected</li>
                    <li>Fitness happens consistently</li>
                    <li>All areas get regular attention</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The structure without monotony:</strong> Provides routine but allows flexibility within blocks</p>
            </div>

            <div class="insight-box">
                <strong>Why block scheduling works for ADHD:</strong> Structure without rigidity, variety without chaos, planning without overwhelm.
                <br><br>
                <strong>The result:</strong> You maintain attention to all important areas, reduce decision fatigue, and increase overall productivity and life balance.
            </div>
        </div>


        <!-- FRAMEWORK 3: FEELINGS WHEEL & VALUES -->
        <div class="section page-break">
            <h2>❤️ Framework #3: Feelings Wheel & Values Clarification</h2>

            <div class="key-quote">
                "Experience with knowledge is usually empty. But once I get there and I see it and I see how it is, now I know I feel it. I experience it."
            </div>

            <h3>The Three-Step Process</h3>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">1</span> List All Stakeholders</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> Identify every group that interacts with your business</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Your stakeholder groups:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li><strong>Your Clients</strong> — The people who hire your services</li>
                    <li><strong>Your Clients' Clients</strong> — The end users/customers your clients serve</li>
                    <li><strong>Your Employees</strong> — Staff members, contractors, team</li>
                    <li><strong>Your Vendors</strong> — Suppliers, partners, service providers</li>
                    <li><strong>Your Community</strong> — Broader impact, industry peers</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Clarifying who you serve helps focus your values work</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">2</span> Define the Feelings You Want Each Group to Experience</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> For each stakeholder group, identify the emotional experience you want them to have</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Use the Feelings Wheel to guide you</strong></p>
                
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Example for "Your Clients":</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>When they call the front desk: <strong>Welcomed, valued, heard</strong></li>
                    <li>During service delivery: <strong>Confident, supported, relieved</strong></li>
                    <li>When receiving billing: <strong>Clarity, fairness, transparency</strong></li>
                    <li>After project completion: <strong>Satisfied, accomplished, grateful</strong></li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Example for "Your Employees":</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Daily work environment: <strong>Respected, empowered, clear on expectations</strong></li>
                    <li>When receiving feedback: <strong>Supported, motivated to grow</strong></li>
                    <li>During challenges: <strong>Backed, not alone, capable</strong></li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The key insight:</strong> "Your mission and values and purpose — those should come from feelings."</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4><span class="step-number">3</span> Use These Feelings to Inform Mission, Values & Brand Identity</h4>
                <p><strong>What this means:</strong> Your clarified emotional goals become the foundation for everything else</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>How feelings inform your business:</strong></p>
                
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Mission Statement:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Built around the experience you create, not just what you do</li>
                    <li>Example: If clients should feel "confident and supported," mission reflects partnership and expertise</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Company Values:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Direct connection to desired feelings</li>
                    <li>Example: Want employees to feel "empowered"? Value might be "Growth Through Autonomy"</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Brand Identity:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Visual design, messaging, tone reflect emotional goals</li>
                    <li>Example: Want clients to feel "welcomed"? Brand should be warm, approachable, accessible</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Operational Decisions:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Policies and processes designed to create desired feelings</li>
                    <li>Example: Want transparency in billing? Create clear, upfront pricing with detailed breakdowns</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>The therapist's metaphor:</strong> Your operations manager as a "property manager" — someone who "takes care of everything" — illustrates how clear roles create the "supported" feeling for clients</p>
            </div>

            <div class="strength-box">
                <h4>✓ Why This Framework Creates Impact</h4>
                <p><strong>Authenticity:</strong> Values rooted in real emotional experiences, not generic corporate speak</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Cohesion:</strong> Every decision and touchpoint aligns with emotional goals</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Differentiation:</strong> Emotional experience is what clients remember and return for</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Clarity:</strong> Guides decision-making when you're unsure what to do next</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Employee engagement:</strong> Team understands not just what to do, but why and how it should feel</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- MEDICATION PLAN -->
        <div class="section page-break">
            <h2>💊 Your Medication Plan</h2>

            <div class="med-box">
                <h4>Vyvanse (Long-Acting Stimulant)</h4>
                <p><strong>Current Dosage:</strong> Small dose (may increase to 20mg as needed)</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Timing:</strong> Take in the morning</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Purpose:</strong> Provides steady, long-acting focus and motivation for ADHD</p>
                
                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>How to take:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>Take in the morning with or without food</li>
                    <li>Swallow capsule whole (do not open or crush)</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="margin-top:15px;"><strong>Expected benefits:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 2;">
                    <li>All-day coverage for focus</li>
                    <li>Sustained motivation and productivity</li>
                    <li>Subtle, smooth effect without peaks and crashes</li>
                    <li>Better executive functioning throughout day</li>
