            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>Psychological vs. Physiological Dependency</h4>
                
                <p><strong>Psychological Dependency:</strong></p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;">Feeling like you "need" medication to function, even if not physically addicted.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Example:</strong> People who take anxiety meds for flying may panic if they forget their meds — not because of the flight, but because they lack the medication.</p>
                
                <p style="margin-top:20px;"><strong>Physiological Dependency:</strong></p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;">The body adapting to medication, requiring higher doses for the same effect.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>The mechanism:</strong> Brain reduces its own neurotransmitter production when medication consistently provides them.</p>

                <p style="margin-top:20px;"><strong>In your life:</strong> Weekend medication breaks prevent both types of dependency</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>Tolerance</h4>
                <p>The brain can "taper back" its own production of neurotransmitters if medication is used constantly, leading to higher dose requirements.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>The therapist's explanation:</strong> "The brain is supposed to do the job, but your brain is like, 'Oh, well, something else is doing that. I can stop.' That's how people get used to a medication and then they need higher doses."</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Prevention:</strong> Taking breaks allows brain to maintain its natural production</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>Block Scheduling</h4>
                <p>A method of organizing time into broad categories, allowing flexibility and regular attention to all important areas.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>In your life:</strong> Instead of rigid routines or complete chaos, you have structured blocks that ensure balanced attention to personal development, work, family, and other priorities.</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Why it works for ADHD:</strong> Provides structure without monotony, variety without overwhelm</p>
            </div>

            <div class="workflow-step">
                <h4>Experience vs. Knowledge</h4>
                <p>The therapist's insight: "Experience with knowledge is usually empty. But once I get there and I see it and I see how it is, now I know I feel it. I experience it."</p>
                <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Applied to business:</strong> Stakeholders remember how you made them feel, not just what services you provided. Emotional experience creates lasting impact and loyalty.</p>
            </div>
